    It uses react-query's useInfiniteQuery for efficient pagination and data fetching.

    The component provides:

    • Infinite scrolling for job listings
    • Search filtering based on URL parameters
    • Normalized job data formatting
    • Navigation to individual job details

(inner) RecentSearches(props) → {JSX.Element|null}

Description:

  • Recent Searches component for displaying user's search history

Example
// Each search object is expected to have this structure:
const searchItem = {
  label: "Frontend Developer",    // Display text
  query: "frontend-developer",    // Search query to execute
  filters: {                      // Optional filters that were applied
    location: "Remote",
    experience: "2-5 years"
  },
  timestamp: 1678954321000        // When the search was performed
};
Parameters:
Name Type Description
props Object

Component props

Properties
Name Type Description
recentSearches Array

Array of recent search objects
onSearchClick function

Handler for when a search is clicked
onClearOne function

Handler for removing a single search item
onClearAll function

Handler for clearing all search history
formatTimestamp function

Function to format timestamp to readable string
Returns:
  • Returns the search history UI or null if no search history
Type
JSX.Element | null

(inner) RecentSearchesContainer() → {JSX.Element}

Description:

  • RecentSearchesContainer component manages recent job search history.

    This component tracks, stores, and displays the user's recent job searches.
    It handles the persistence of search data in localStorage, formatting search labels,
    and provides functionality to navigate to previous searches or clear the search history.

Example
return (
  <RecentSearchesContainer />
)
Returns:

The Recent Searches component with populated data and event handlers

  },
  timestamp: 1678954321000        // When the search was performed
